image.altText: Item found during Samantha Murphy search

props.synopsis: Divers were employed to search a dam on a property south of Ballarat on Wednesday, as detectives recovered a phone during a fresh search for evidence.

title.children: Victoria Police to forensically test new 'items of interest' found in search for Samantha Murphy

image.altText: A mock up of the live nation and ticketmaster logos on a phone

props.synopsis: The personal details of thousands of Australian customers may have been leaked in the alleged data breach.

title.children: Australians among 560 million users around the world caught in Ticketmaster hack

image.altText: A box full of packets of illegal cigarettes.

props.synopsis: The black market for cigarettes has exploded in plain sight, costing Australia billions in revenue. Some experts say the high price of cigarettes is to blame.

title.children: In a black market, illegal deals are made in plain sight over the counter of everyday convenience stores

image.altText: Matthew Roberts

props.synopsis: Sex workers can now fight "debanking" in some parts of Australia, but others are left hiding their jobs and battling financial discrimination.

title.children: 'Tap and go': The sex worker who fought 'debanking' and got his EFTPOS machine back

image.altText: Andrew Giles speaks at a press conference at parliament house

props.synopsis: Andrew Giles is facing immense pressure over the decision known as Direction 99, but he shows no signs of going anywhere. This mess can be traced back to a meeting of two prime ministers looking to repair a broken relationship.

title.children: Albanese is standing by his immigration minister, but this time he can't blame the mess on the High Court

image.altText: Sam Millard and Samantha Lilley in a graphic is censored comments from Facebook

props.synopsis: Short statured Australians say photos taken of them without consent are being increasingly distributed and mocked online. They're sick of it and want the wider public to help call it out.

title.children: 'It's become a bit of a sport': The 'disgusting' online abuse faced by Sam and her community

image.altText: The inside of a warehouse with rows and stacks of soft plastic bundles.

props.synopsis: The deadline for Coles and Woolworths to deal with thousands of tonnes of soft plastic waste left in the collapse of REDcycle has again been extended, in hopes it can be spared from landfill.

title.children: Coles and Woolworths given more time to deal with stranded REDcycle plastic waste

image.altText: An image of two Israeli tanks with soldiers on top of them, on the right is an Israeli flag.

props.synopsis: Israel has sent tanks on raids into Rafah and said its war on Hamas in Gaza would likely continue all year, after Washington said the Rafah assault did not amount to a major ground operation that would trigger a change in US policy.

title.children: Israel says Gaza war likely to last another seven months as tanks probe Rafah

image.altText: Bright orange lava erupts from the black ground as smoke pours into the sky

props.synopsis: People have been evacuated from a nearby town and popular tourist destination, as Iceland grapples with the latest eruption.

title.children: Icelandic volcano erupts for fifth time after 400 earthquakes hit the area in a week

image.altText: A composite of a man wearing glasses and a yellow scarf next to an AI generated image of the same man.

props.synopsis: Muthuvel Karunanidhi, an iconic Indian actor-turned-politician, made a surprising appearance in January ahead of the Indian election despite being dead for six years. It’s a sign of how deepfakes have influenced this year’s campaign.

title.children: Are deepfakes the frightening future of election campaigns? India is already there

image.altText: Two  women walk past the Reserve Bank of Australia headquarters, with the building's name prominent in the background.

props.synopsis: Inflation is rising again, and that's a problem for both the government and the Reserve Bank, writes David Taylor.

title.children: RBA should now 'in theory' hike interest rates in June, but will it?

image.altText: Woman holding bottle of drink on light blue background, closeup

props.synopsis: Is your water bottle etched with words of encouragement, urging you to "keep chugging" because you're "almost there"? What happens if you don't drink up?

title.children: How much water should you drink? Don't trust your water bottle

image.altText: A young woman and man stand next to a vandalised car

props.synopsis: An insurance policy clause means some victims of a vandalism spree won't receive a cent, but others will be fully covered.

title.children: Suburb hit by vandalism spree, but some victims won't receive a cent from insurers

image.altText: A close up shot of Peter Dutton in glasses.

props.synopsis: The opposition leader hits back after the government tries to blunt his attacks on Immigration Minister Andrew Giles by highlighting the release of criminals during Peter Dutton's tenure as minister.

title.children: 'I cancelled more than 6,300 visas': Dutton hits back as government tries to blunt attacks on Andrew Giles

image.altText: A close-up shot of an older woman with blonde hair looking to her right, with another blonde woman on her left.

props.synopsis: The sister of Lynn Cannon, who was killed by her estranged husband in Perth, says her family's tragedy has been repeated by the Floreat murders.

title.children: As people come to terms with yet another DV murder, the families of women killed by men shake their heads

image.altText: A tight head and shoulders shot of WA Police Commissioner Col Blanch speaking while wearing his police uniform.

props.synopsis: Authorities in WA have leapt to defend the way police responded to concerns raised by the wife and daughter of Floreat double murderer Mark Bombara prior to the shootings.

title.children: WA police commissioner says it's 'wrong' to say nothing was done prior to Floreat murders

image.altText: A side profile close up of Peter Dutton.

props.synopsis: Peter Dutton's political survival as an opposition leader thus far is an impressive feat, but the issue of nuclear power could be one that damages his popularity with women, a new piece of research shows.

title.children: Peter Dutton's a political freak of nature, but is he about to nuke himself with women voters?

image.altText: A young couple stand arm in arm in front of a motel door, she smiles at the camera he smiles at her

props.synopsis: A family who for months had been sleeping rough were able to land jobs and a home when they checked into a country motel for a night of reprieve from the cold. They are seeing more and more people booking rooms as a long-term option.

title.children: Locked out of the rental market, families are turning to motels and caravan parks

image.altText: A forensic scientist examines a knife under a fluorescent light.

props.synopsis: Hidden behind a towering electric fence in a regional Victorian city, a team of 11 forensic scientists is helping police catch criminals. The ABC takes a look inside the secretive, high-tech facility.

title.children: The high-security forensic hub where women outnumber men, as they expose the devil in the detail

image.altText: land clearing 1

props.synopsis: Unauthorised bulldozing of "really important" native vegetation has landed NSW Southern Highlands property owner Chaza Khouzame a $125,000 fine, plus costs.

title.children: Landowner fined $125,000 after ignoring orders to stop clearing native bush, 200-year-old trees

image.altText: BHP chief executive Andrew Mackenzie silhouetted with logo in the background

props.synopsis: Anglo American has rejected BHP Group's last-ditch request for more time to discuss a $74 billion takeover offer, dismissing it as highly complex and likely ending a five-week pursuit by the bigger rival.

title.children: Anglo American rejects BHP's last-ditch attempt to continue takeover talks

image.altText: Hannah sings into a microphone in a frilly pink dress with white underwear on display. A shirtless man plays a pink piano.

props.synopsis: It's Pay Day! Australian drag superstar Hannah Conda explains the expensive reality behind the scenes of her glitzy appearances on RuPaul's Drag Race, and the travel mistake that led her to the lowest point in her financial life.

title.children: The $4,000 travelling mistake that left drag superstar Hannah Conda at the 'lowest point in her financial life'

image.altText: Eight items of clothing are hung on black clothes hangers, including three singlets, three pairs of pants, and a white shirt.

props.synopsis: Whether you shop in-store or online, retailers are ramping up sales to entice us to part with our cash. But, as spending flatlines, discounting doesn't appear to have the same effect it used to, sparking warnings of looming retail collapses.

title.children: If you've noticed almost every retail store is having a sale right now, it's because they are. Here's why

image.altText: Laura Tingle at a podium at the National Press Club.

props.synopsis: ABC News director Justin Stevens says comments made by political journalist Laura Tingle at Sydney Writers' Festival did not meet the organisation's editorial standards.

title.children: ABC says Laura Tingle's Sydney Writers' Festival comments did not meet editorial standards

image.altText: A woman wearing a black suede shirt sits in a large green chair and smiles.

props.synopsis: After losing her son to suicide six years ago, Kate Slatter thought she knew how to handle complex grief. But it was after the sudden death of another close family member that she found herself overwhelmed and in need of an end-of-life expert carer.

title.children: How end-of-life doulas are changing the way people think about death

image.altText: The back of a police officer looking towards damaged and overturned carriages

props.synopsis: Rail authorities were alerted to the fatal consequences of a train and truck crash in SA's north when a member of the public answered one of the dead drivers' phones, a preliminary report by the Australian Transport Safety Bureau finds.

title.children: Member of the public picked up dead train driver's phone after horrific truck crash, ATSB reveals

image.altText: Two police officers stand in front of crime scene tape in a dark street

props.synopsis: Police and paramedics were called to a home in Adelaide's Western suburbs following reports of an unresponsive child. The girl was treated at the scene before being taken to hospital where she has died.

title.children: Major crime investigating after 5yo girl dies in Adelaide

image.altText: Giles gestures with one hand and looks confused, sitting in the lower house.

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese says a new ministerial direction will be issued to deal with cases of visa cancellations in the wake of an individual whose visa was reinstated being accused of murder in Brisbane.

title.children: Government to issue new directive prioritising community safety when considering visa cancellations

image.altText: A close-up shot of a shopping trolley full of groceries in a supermarket with a woman behind bagging apples.

props.synopsis: The annual rate of inflation has ticked up slightly in April to 3.6 per cent, from 3.5 per cent in March, but economists say it's enough to put even more pressure on the Reserve Bank.

title.children: Inflation rises slightly in April to 3.6pc but economists say that should ring 'alarm bells' for RBA

image.altText: A skull from the side, with E270 on one side, and a crater like hole at the top

props.synopsis: Researchers have uncovered what look like surgery marks on an ancient Egyptian skull with remains of a tumour-like growth, suggesting ancient Egyptians not only got cancer, they may also have tried to treat it.

title.children: An ancient treatment for cancer? 4,000-year-old Egyptian skull a 'milestone in the history of medicine'

image.altText: A child rests in her mother's arms while surrounded by debris and garbage.

props.synopsis: Palestinian civilians in Gaza hoped that last week's ruling from the International Court of Justice might represent a turning point, but it has quickly turned into an argument about legal interpretation and world order.

title.children: A court ruling on Israel's invasion of Rafah has turned into a complicated legal argument. Here's why

image.altText: Woman with blonde hair looking to camera with black background

props.synopsis: A former gymnast says while the payments are by no means compensation for the mental and physical harm endured, they are at least something tangible.

title.children: Former WAIS gymnasts to be offered $15,000 for harm caused by coaching practices

image.altText: An egg carton with eggs of varying hues in it.

props.synopsis: Japan has joined the United States in banning poultry imports from Victoria, as the state works to control two outbreaks of avian influenza.

title.children: Japan, US among countries to ban Victorian poultry imports due to bird flu

image.altText: A smiling man in a cap stands in a paddock with rice growing in it.

props.synopsis: Australian rice growers have mixed views about the biggest shake-up of the industry in 100 years, but change is on the way.

title.children: SunRice monopoly set to end, Australian growers eye new markets

image.altText: Bob Rogers

props.synopsis: Australia's longest serving disc jockey Bob Rogers has died at his Mosman home this morning. He was 97. Rogers has a 78-year broadcasting career working for radio stations all over Australia.

title.children: 'A radio icon': Legendary broadcaster Bob Rogers dies aged 97
